[]: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Quote Post by Kendrix &raquo; Wed May 28, 2014 7:36 am Some of the dialogue/motifs used there are clearly meant to in invoke &quot;basic fond romance memory tropes&#39; - it sounds poetic in itself, like ep 24&#39;s &quot;the password is our first memory&quot; - We never learn what that is, either. But if Anno had an actual line in mind, I&#39;m pretty certain it was &quot;Marry me.&quot; Because of the entire Christmas Cake complex subplot and Misato being griped about it in eps 1 and 15, when she and Ritsuko were conversing about how all their same-age friends were getting married by the dozen and Ritsuko jibs her about &#39;just being afraid she&#39;ll be left over&#39; Then, she gets some unexpected smoochies of her own in that same episode... yeah. It&#39;s a motif~ While they already have Asuka and Shinji for children and might even go on to formally adopt them, I don&#39;t think either of them would be too keen about the procreating, if they had a kid, it would be because, &quot;Ooops, I forgot the pill from all the morning beer&quot;. It&#39;d probably involve Ritsuko, and Asuka gleefully destroying all the alcohol and caffeine in their dwellings.... Of course, that bubble was popped already when that SEELE goon got him

[]: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Quote Post by obliterates &raquo; Wed May 28, 2014 8:18 am Remember this is Japanese culture we are talking about. Even many married couples go their whole lives without hearing the words &quot;I love you&quot; in its formal sense. While I&#39;m sure Misato heard the words &quot;Suki&quot; and even &quot;daisuki&quot; &#40;I love you/I adore you&#41; in college, she never got the committed, formal declaration of undying love: &quot;aishiteru&quot;. Finally, he planned on saying it to her now. I can&#39;t see it likely that Kaji and Misato would get married, even with a recognized formal declaration of love. Misato comes from a divorced home, Kaji has no family whatsoever: that&#39;s really not any grounds to get engaged in a Japanese society. And I&#39;m sure Misato has a lot of hangups surrounding &quot;marriage&quot; and &quot;revenge and duty&quot;. I can imagine her, after getting over her shock, saying no. Kaji probably already knows about this anyway. Marriage and love can be mutually exclusive. Also, in on of the Eva Panchinko games, Kaji actually says the words: and all it is &quot;Aishiteruze, Katsuragi.&quot; That&#39;s a pretty big bomb by itself, marriage proposal or no.

